[[span class="greent"]]THE[[/span]] FAQ
[[/div]]

[[div class="pseudomain"]]
**Hell, I like this event! I have a draft, where and who do I send it to?**
Send [[*user Uncle Nicolini]] a Wikidot DM with a link to your draft. Once the swap starts, we will send you someone else's draft to work on!

**What qualifies as a draft?**
Drafts should be more than simply an idea: you should already have put some work into developing the idea, figuring out rules and structure, writing some parts out, etc. You don't have to have a lot done, but we won't be accepting anything that's nothing more than a title. If you have any questions on whether or not what you have qualifies, send [[*user Queerious]] or [[*user Uncle Nicolini]] a DM!

**My draft is kind of hard to write without my perspective/knowledge. Is that okay?**
While it is preferable for a draft to be easy to understand (for example, NOT high level science, deep fandom lore, specific historical accuracy), you can submit a draft with that subject matter. Although, if you do do so, you should be committed to sticking around in chat to help out and provide information.

**If I want to post what I wrote, do I need to credit the original author as a co-author?**
Before posting, you should ask the original author what they would like, and go along with that.

**I've put a lot of thought into my draft, but most of it isn't on the actual page. Is that okay?**
If this is the case for you, I'd suggest including a note to the recipient explaining ideas you had for the draft, what you wanted to get across with it, etc. They're not beholden to it, but it might help them.

If you're active in Deer College chat, you can also just talk directly to whoever gets your draft and chat/brainstorm with them about it.
[[/div]] 
